  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Building UK Capacity in BST to improve effectiveness in South Africa</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Bishop Simeon Trust (BST) supports the most disadvantaged South Africans who still suffer from the social and economic legacy of Apartheid. They focus on very marginal communities, building capacity to solve problems and meet the needs of very poor, the disabled and those suffering from HIV and associated illnesses. Their projects have been successful but the UK organisation has not advanced much. It has minimal staff and few unrestricted reserves which are not often used in a strategic way to build the capacity of BST but as ad hoc help to partners. BST needs to change. Its supporter base in the UK is aging and it cannot respond as dynamically as it would like to new priorities and opportunities. BST wants to make what they do more lasting, learn and share more with others, and have a greater impact. Both BST and its partners need to find a more sustainable model, new approaches to fundraising and less of a &#xE2;&#x20AC;&#x2DC;hand to mouth&apos; existence. BST has a new Chairman and several new Trustees, including the Treasurer, with the founders now gone or only occupying honorary positions. This represents an historic opportunity to rethink BST&apos;s future, its messages and communication strategy, and unite around this.</narrative>
  </description>
